@NODE Utilities "Cloanto - The Kara Collection - Utilities"
@TOC Main

@{B}Utilities@{UB}

The "Utilities" drawer in The Kara Collection CD-ROM contains some useful
support tools, which are described here.


@{B}Install@{UB}

This procedure uses the Amiga Installer software to selectively install
program, font and data files to the hard disk. Before proceeding, it
checks whether there is enough room on the disk to install the selected
items. Since hard disk space is more expensive than CD-ROM storage, some
graphics files (palette-based Plaquegrounds and other pictures) are
automatically installed in formats which are more space efficient (but
take slightly longer to load) than the corresponding files on the CD-ROM.

Unless the entire CD-ROM is installed (using the special installation
option), tutorial animations are installed only in the format which is
determined to work best, and documentation files in languages other than
the one currently selected are not installed. Some manual files may
contain links to other items which have not been installed. Such links
work only when the CD-ROM is present, or after these additional items have
been installed.

The section which (optionally) installs the Personal Paint upgrade asks
for the serial number of the original Personal Paint or Personal Suite
package, and only works if an older (non-Demo) version of Personal Paint
is already installed.

Depending on which items are installed, the installation procedure may add
a number of "Assign" commands to the "User-Startup" file. On certain
versions of the operating system, Assign commands are not effective if a
disk or CD-ROM is present having the same name as the Assign logical name.
In particular, the "KaraCD:" logical name may not be assigned if the
"KaraCD" CD-ROM is also in use. If this happens, either the CD-ROM must
not be in the drive while the system is booted, or the CD-ROM device must
be made available to the system only after the execution of the Assign
command.


@{B}SetPPView@{UB}

All pictures and animations on the CD-ROM are associated to a "Default
Tool" named "PPView" which by default uses Personal Paint to view any
artwork selected with a double-click. The demonstration version of
Personal Paint included on the CD-ROM serves this purpose without
limitations. However, some Amiga users may prefer to use a different
viewer, such as MultiView or Viewtek. The SetPPView utility can be used to
define a different viewer than Personal Paint for pictures, and another
viewer for animations.

From a technical point of view, the viewers are set by defining the
"PPViewPic" and "PPViewAnim" Amiga environment variables. The variables
may contain the name of the new viewer, followed by some optional
parameters. PPView always executes the specified viewer passing the
artwork file as a parameter. The position of the artwork file parameter
can be determined by placing square brackets ("[]") with nothing between
them in the definition string, just as in the AmigaDOS Alias command.

These are examples of viewer definitions (defined manually from the Shell,
rather than using SetPPView):

   SetEnv PPViewPic "MultiView SCREEN"

   SetEnv PPViewAnim "VT [] SC=MULTISCAN:Productivity"

Certain slide show procedures launched by links in AmigaGuide documents
and through various "ViewAll" icons on the CD-ROM need to interact
directly with Personal Paint via Rexx, without using the PPView tool.
Therefore, these procedures are not affected by SetPPView.


@{B}AssignFonts@{UB}

The Amiga operating system normally searches for font files wherever the
"FONTS:" logical name is assigned to. By default, this does not include
the fonts on The Kara Collection. The CD-ROM configurations scripts
automatically update "FONTS:" to include all the fonts which are on the
CD-ROM, so that all programs can find them. From version 2.0 of the Amiga
operating system, a logical name such as "FONTS:" can be assigned to more
than one directory. The automatic configuration uses this feature, if
available, in order to add the new font path while at the same time
preserving the existing path references, so that programs looking for a
font can scan different locations.

The AssignFonts utility is provided to manually reassign "FONTS:" to any
directory containing Amiga fonts. A file requester appears, asking the
user to select the new directory.

Certain programs (e.g. Deluxe Paint) may search the "FONTS:" directory for
a particular font which is required in order to render their screen texts.
If AssignFonts is used to change the "FONTS:" assignment to a directory
which does not contain the required font, then these programs may not run
properly. In this case, AssignFonts should be run only after the software
is launched, or it can be used to restore a specific path before running
the software. Programs such as Personal Paint and ColorType, which also
use a custom font for their user interface, are not disturbed by
AssignFonts.


@{B}ColorText@{UB}

This utility is only required with versions of the Amiga operating system
which do not support ColorFonts (versions prior to 2.0). The ColorText
program adds support for ColorFonts to older operating systems. ColorText
is activated with a simple double-click.


@{B}"Script" DataType@{UB}

Some of the document icons on the CD-ROM are not associated directly to a
text, but rather to an AmigaDOS command script which in turn opens a
document in the correct language and with the correct viewing software
depending on the system configuration.

When the documents are viewed with a double-click on their icon, the
transition from the AmigaDOS script to the AmigaGuide document is
performed automatically. If instead "drag and drop" is used with a
combination of programs like ToolManager and MultiView, then a DataType
such as "Script" is required. Otherwise, the viewing software displays a
series of AmigaDOS commands instead of the intended AmigaGuide document.

The "Script" DataType recognizes and executes AmigaDOS command scripts
which are normally processed by the system IconX tool. DataTypes are
supported from version 3.0 of the Amiga operating system.


